    <h1>Economy of Research</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Chapter 7 · Peirce 1879, Chamberlin 1890, Platt 1964, de Kleer 1987, Hintikka 1999</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">You have ten hypotheses and budget for three experiments. Which three? Chapters 4&ndash;6 formalized the abductive primitive &mdash; diff, bi-abduction, tri-abduction. The primitive generates hypotheses. This chapter selects among them.</p>
    </div>

    <p>Hypothesis generation is cheap. Testing is expensive. Every experiment costs time, compute, reagents, or attention. The abductive primitive can produce dozens of candidate explanations from a single surprising observation. Running all of them is rarely feasible. The question is which subset to test, in what order, and when to stop.</p>

    <p>This problem has a 150-year history. Peirce formalized it first, in 1879. Chamberlin addressed the cognitive prerequisite in 1890. Platt operationalized it in 1964. De Kleer and Williams automated it in 1987. Hintikka gave it game-theoretic foundations in the 1990s. The modern machine-learning literature often develops similar criteria without foregrounding the abductive context.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>Peirce: marginal return on research investment (1879)</h2>

    <p>In "Note on the Theory of the Economy of Research," Peirce made the allocation problem explicit: given a fixed budget, how should you allocate it across experiments to maximize what you learn?</p>

    <p>His answer used the language of marginal analysis. Each additional dollar spent on an experiment yields some increment of knowledge. That increment diminishes as you pour more resources into the same line of inquiry. The optimal allocation equalizes the marginal return per dollar across all active experiments. If experiment A yields more information per dollar than experiment B, shift budget from B to A until the marginals equalize.</p>

    <p>Peirce derived a specific result: the optimal sample size for an experiment depends on the ratio of the utility of the information to the cost of each observation. High-utility, low-cost experiments should get large samples. Low-utility, high-cost experiments should get small samples or be skipped entirely. This is obvious in retrospect, but Peirce was among the first to formalize it.</p>

    <blockquote>
      <p>"The doctrine of economy, in general, treats of the relations between utility and cost. The economy of research is that particular application of it which gives the rules for the expenditure of money, energy, and time upon the different elements of an investigation."</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">&mdash; Peirce, "Note on the Theory of the Economy of Research" (1879)</p>
    </blockquote>

    <p>This predates Wald's sequential analysis (1947) by 68 years. Wald asked: given a stream of data, when should you stop collecting and make a decision? Peirce asked the prior question: given multiple possible experiments, which stream should you open? Wald's work became a field. Peirce's note received little attention until historians of science highlighted it in the 1960s.</p>

    <h2>Chamberlin: breadth before depth (1890)</h2>

    <p><a href="/reading/scientific-method/chamberlin-1890/">Chamberlin's "Method of Multiple Working Hypotheses"</a> addresses the cognitive prerequisite for economy of research. You cannot select optimally among hypotheses you haven't generated. And you will not generate hypotheses that compete with your favorite if you have a favorite.</p>

    <p>Chamberlin's argument is structural, not statistical. A scientist who holds one ruling theory will unconsciously steer experiments toward confirmation. The data that fits is amplified; the data that doesn't is explained away. The remedy is to hold multiple hypotheses simultaneously, without ranking, and let the data sort the field.</p>

    <p>For economy of research, Chamberlin supplies the input. Before you can ask "which experiment next?" you need a set of candidate hypotheses broad enough that the true explanation is likely among them. Chamberlin's method generates that set. Peirce's economy selects from it.</p>

