    <h2>Platt: strong inference as a selection protocol (1964)</h2>

    <p><a href="/reading/scientific-method/platt-1964/">Platt</a> operationalized Chamberlin into a loop: enumerate alternative hypotheses, design a crucial experiment that excludes at least one, run it, repeat. His contribution to economy of research is the concept of the <em>crucial experiment</em> &mdash; an experiment whose outcome eliminates one or more hypotheses regardless of which way it goes.</p>

    <p>Crucial experiments are maximally economical. A non-crucial experiment can confirm a hypothesis without eliminating any alternatives. It spends budget without shrinking the hypothesis space. A crucial experiment guarantees that the hypothesis space shrinks with every run. Platt observed that fields practicing strong inference &mdash; molecular biology, particle physics &mdash; moved faster than fields that didn't &mdash; psychology, ecology. The rate difference tracks the fraction of experiments that are crucial.</p>

    <p>Platt's framework is qualitative. He tells you what a good experiment looks like (crucial) but not how to find the best one among several crucial alternatives. For that, you need de Kleer.</p>

    <h2>De Kleer &amp; Williams: GDE and computed experiment selection (1987)</h2>

    <p>The General Diagnostic Engine (GDE) was an influential early system that computed which measurement to take next from the structure of remaining hypotheses. The context was circuit diagnosis. A chip has a fault. Multiple components could be responsible. Each measurement (probing a node) has a cost and yields information about which components are healthy or faulty.</p>

    <p>GDE maintains a set of <em>candidate diagnoses</em> &mdash; minimal sets of faulty components consistent with all observations so far. Given this set, it computes the information-theoretic value of each possible measurement: how much does probing node X reduce the entropy of the diagnosis distribution? It then selects the measurement with the highest information gain per unit cost.</p>

    <p>The algorithm is straightforward:</p>

    <ol class="list-decimal pl-5 mb-4">
      <li class="mb-1">Enumerate remaining candidate diagnoses, each with a probability.</li>
      <li class="mb-1">For each possible measurement, compute the expected posterior entropy over diagnoses.</li>
      <li class="mb-1">Subtract from the current entropy to get expected information gain.</li>
      <li class="mb-1">Divide by measurement cost. Select the measurement with the highest ratio.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>GDE connected Peirce's economy (marginal information per dollar) to Platt's crucial experiments (maximize elimination) to Shannon's information theory (entropy reduction). It did this for a specific domain &mdash; circuit diagnosis &mdash; but the architecture generalizes. Replace "circuit component" with "hypothesis" and "probe node" with "experiment" and you have the economy of research, automated.</p>

    <h2>Hintikka: inquiry as a game (1988/1999)</h2>

    <p>Jaakko Hintikka recast investigation as a two-player game between the Inquirer and Nature. The Inquirer asks questions (runs experiments). Nature answers (provides data). The Inquirer's strategy determines which question to ask next based on previous answers. The goal is to reach a definite conclusion with minimum total cost.</p>

    <p>Hintikka's interrogative model connects directly to Peirce's abduction. Each question the Inquirer poses is an abductive act: "If hypothesis H were true, what would I observe at measurement point X?" The answer either supports H or eliminates it. The Inquirer's optimal strategy is the economy of research expressed as a game tree.</p>

    <p>The game-theoretic framing adds something the information-theoretic framing misses: the next question depends on previous answers. GDE recomputes from scratch after each measurement. Hintikka's model encodes the dependency structure. The Inquirer's strategy is not a ranking of experiments but a policy &mdash; a function from the history of observations to the next question. This is the difference between a sorted list and a decision tree.</p>

